drinking of alcohol or coffee is
OK.

21:30.990 --> 21:35.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help guide us through some of
these guidelines,
their impact and the
controversy, I'm joined

21:35.294 --> 21:38.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by Allison Aubrey, food and
health correspondent
for NPR.

21:38.731 --> 21:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, Allison, let's start with
sugar first.

21:41.467 --> 21:43.269 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY, NPR: Sure.

21:43.302 --> 21:45.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What is the
right amount
of sugar? And put it in terms I
can understand.

21:45.704 --> 21:47.473 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALLISON AUBREY: Sure.

21:47.506 --> 21:50.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, basically, the dietary
guidelines are
coming out and saying you should
get no more

21:50.509 --> 21:56.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than 10 percent of your calories
per day from
sugar, and that translates to
about 10 to

21:56.248 --> 22:03.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
12-teaspoons per day. Now, keep
in mind, this
adds up really, really quickly.
It translates

22:03.088 --> 22:07.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to about maybe 40 grams of
sugar. That's the
unit of measurement that people
are used to

22:07.526 --> 22:09.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
seeing on labels.

22:09.395 --> 22:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for instance, this morning,
I had a yogurt
for breakfast that had about 20
grams of sugar.

22:14.767 --> 22:20.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You had one sort of sugary drink
or one muffin,
you're at your daily limit. And
basically,

22:20.906 --> 22:25.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right now, Americans are eating
about twice
as much. We have reported on
studies that

22:25.878 --> 22:29.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
show that many Americans are
eating 22 teaspoons
a day.

22:29.982 --> 22:34.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if people are going to start
following
these recommendations, it really
means cutting

22:34.220 --> 22:35.955 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
consumption of sugar in half.

22:35.988 --> 22:38.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
maybe that will
help keep my New Year's
resolution going.

22:38.724 --> 22:43.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, let's also talk about the
change, it seems,
about eggs and cholesterol. Why
the change?

22:43.896 --> 22:48.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Well, it's been
sort of evolving
nutrition science, I would say.

22:48.567 --> 22:55.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There used to be a belief that
if you were
to eat a lot of cholesterol-rich
foods, so

22:55.274 --> 23:01.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
animal-based foods with
cholesterol, think
of eggs or shrimp, that that
high cholesterol

23:01.213 --> 23:05.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
would lead to high LDL
cholesterol in your
bloodstream.

23:05.918 --> 23:10.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there is still clearly a
concern about
elevated cholesterol in
bloodstream. That's

23:10.289 --> 23:15.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
why many, many Americans are on
statins. But
it's now recognized that
high-cholesterol

23:15.561 --> 23:20.532 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
foods don't necessarily
translate into higher
cholesterol in our blood.

23:20.566 --> 23:25.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So the
guidelines didn't
say eat less red meat. It said
go ahead and

23:25.704 --> 23:28.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
supplement with more seafood and
other things.
Why?

23:28.607 --> 23:34.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Well, I think
what the goal
is that one of the committee
members told

23:34.380 --> 23:39.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me that Americans don't want to
be told what
not to eat, what to avoid. They
want to be

23:39.918 --> 23:44.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
told what they -- how to expand
their diet
or add more variety.

23:44.490 --> 23:50.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the words of the dietary
guidelines
and the people supporting
communication about

23:50.596 --> 23:57.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the new guidelines, the word
they're using
is shift. The idea is to shift
away from meat

23:57.336 --> 24:02.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and try alternative sources of
protein, so
anything from seafood to nuts to
beans.

24:02.441 --> 24:07.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, implicitly, that might mean
eating less
red meat, if you're eating more
of these other

24:07.413 --> 24:15.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sources of protein. It's a
little bit controversial.
The committee that helped advise
the administration

24:15.421 --> 24:19.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on what should be in these
guidelines came
out last year and said, hey, we
think you

24:19.925 --> 24:25.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
should tell Americans to eat
less red meat.
But, in the end, that's not
what's in their

24:25.097 --> 24:26.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dietary guidelines.

24:26.799 --> 24:29.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And what are
nutritionists
or experts in this think as
well?

24:29.535 --> 24:32.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Well, there is
some criticism,
I have to say, today.

24:32.371 --> 24:40.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have spoken to several top
nutrition researchers
who say a limit on red meat
really should

24:40.279 --> 24:45.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have been put into the
guidelines. Otherwise,
Americans might just be confused
by this message

24:45.150 --> 24:51.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about shifting. And I think the
range of opinion
goes something like this.

24:51.190 --> 24:54.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some people say, well, if you
are nudging
Americans to eat a little bit
less, that's

24:54.927 --> 25:01.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough. The other point of view
is Americans
need to be told like, hey, there
is too much

25:01.700 --> 25:07.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
red meat in your diet. They need
a specific
limit, but, again, that's not
there.

25:07.072 --> 25:11.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The fact that
these guidelines
come out only once every five
years, it almost

25:11.610 --> 25:18.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
makes it a political document.
It's a statement
by an administration on what
they think the

25:18.250 --> 25:20.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government thinks people should
or shouldn't
eat, right?

25:20.552 --> 25:26.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Well, I don't
see it so much
as a political document, as I
see it as kind

25:26.458 --> 25:28.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a consensus report.

25:28.293 --> 25:32.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a lag factor here. You
pointed out
in the beginning that just now
do we have

25:32.498 --> 25:36.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a recommendation to limit sugar.
Your grandmother
could have told you that too
much sugar is

25:36.335 --> 25:40.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bad for you. And what you have
to understand
is that the way this process
works is that,

25:40.906 --> 25:44.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
every five years, the Department
of Health
and Human Services and the U.S.
Department

25:44.943 --> 25:50.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Agriculture assign this
expert committee
to review all the new evidence.

25:50.649 --> 25:55.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They pore over all of the
nutrition science
and they try to come up with a
consensus.

25:55.721 --> 26:00.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for instance, five years
ago, we knew
that sugar would rot your teeth,
but we didn't

26:00.692 --> 26:05.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know that 22 teaspoons of sugar
a day would
lead to an increased risk of
heart disease

26:05.297 --> 26:07.065 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or diabetes.

26:07.099 --> 26:13.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it takes a while for a
body of evidence
to lead scientists to say, aha,
we need a

26:13.806 --> 26:16.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
clear recommendation here, so a
bit of a lag
time.

26:16.975 --> 26:25.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Allison Aubrey
of NPR, thanks so much for
joining us.

26:26.018 --> 26:31.857 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Thanks for
having me.

26:31.890 --> 26:39.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now: the power of
altruism, not
just for those on the receiving
end, but also

26:39.097 --> 26:43.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how it provides physical and
emotional benefits
for the giver.

26:43.502 --> 26:48.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman takes
a look, part of our weekly
segment Making

26:48.106 --> 26:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sense, which airs every Thursday
on the "NewsHour."

26:50.476 --> 26:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: I want you to meet my
friend Monkey.
Hello. Do you want to say hello?

26:55.314 --> 26:59.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: It is better to
give than to
receive. You may have heard it
when you were

26:59.751 --> 27:05.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about this age, or even in the
past few weeks,
when you bought out the entire
Christmas list.

27:05.290 --> 27:12.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: Look, Monkey has a bowl
just like you.
You don't have any treats and
neither does

27:12.264 --> 27:14.199 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Monkey.

27:14.233 --> 27:17.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But better for
whom? A behavioral
economics experiment has come up
with a provocative

27:17.669 --> 27:18.604 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
answer.

27:18.637 --> 27:20.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: I'm going to give them
all to you.

27:20.906 --> 27:25.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Psychology
professor Elizabeth
Dunn designed this test to see
if even very

27:25.777 --> 27:28.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
young kids could be happier
giving than receiving.

27:29.014 --> 27:31.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN, University of
British Columbia:
We worked with kind of the
toddler equivalent

27:31.383 --> 27:36.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of gold, namely goldfish
crackers. We gave
them a bunch goldfish for
themselves, and

27:36.455 --> 27:40.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then we gave them the chance to
give some
of these goldfish away to a
puppet named Monkey.

27:41.026 --> 27:48.667 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Will you give one to
Monkey? Yes?

27:48.700 --> 27:50.602 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
CHILD: Yes.

27:50.636 --> 27:56.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Dunn recorded
dozens of kids
doing this, then had students
who knew nothing

27:56.475 --> 28:02.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the experiment compare the
facial expressions
when receiving and when giving.
When were

28:02.481 --> 28:04.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the kids happiest?

28:04.349 --> 28:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: What we see is
that the toddlers
are happier when they're getting
the chance

28:07.252 --> 28:11.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to give the goldfish away, as
compared to
when they're getting the
goldfish for themselves.

28:11.423 --> 28:16.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Much happier. So,
it's no surprise
that, with fellow happiness
scholar Michael

28:16.061 --> 28:21.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Norton, Dunn has written a book:
"Happy Money:
The Science of Happier
Spending."

28:21.800 --> 28:23.602 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It features five key takeaways.

28:23.635 --> 28:27.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: Well, if you
want to use money
to buy happiness, we suggest you
should buy

28:27.706 --> 28:33.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experiences, you should buy
time, you should
make it a treat, you should pay
now and consume

28:34.012 --> 28:35.914 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
later, and you should invest in
others.

28:35.948 --> 28:41.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Invest in others,
the most surprising
finding of the five and one
which regularly

28:41.887 --> 28:45.324 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
elicits skepticism, says
business school professor
Michael Norton.

28:45.357 --> 28:47.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL NORTON, Harvard
University: A lot
of people, when we talk about
the fact that

28:47.659 --> 28:52.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
giving makes you happy and
you're better off
giving than spending your money
on yourself,

28:52.464 --> 28:56.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will argue back, first off, that
we're crazy,
and, secondly, that that can't
be true, because

28:56.735 --> 29:02.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't really know what you
like, but I definitely
know what I like. And so, just
by definition,

29:02.374 --> 29:05.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm better at spending my money
on myself
and getting happiness than you,
because I

29:05.978 --> 29:07.346 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
don't know everything about you.

29:07.379 --> 29:11.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Can panda have one? Yes.
Can one go
in his bowl?

29:11.516 --> 29:14.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL NORTON: It's just not
what we see
in this study. So, even with
these toddlers,

29:14.720 --> 29:18.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are 2 years old, even if
it's the case
that their parents are making
them give in

29:18.624 --> 29:21.460 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
order to be a nice person,
they're smiling.

29:21.493 --> 29:25.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And smiling is something that
just comes out.
It's not something that you can
control very

29:25.297 --> 29:27.065 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
well.

29:27.099 --> 29:29.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it's not just
toddlers. Dunn
also designed an experiment for
grownups.

29:30.002 --> 29:33.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: We went out on
our campus
at the University of British
Columbia and

29:33.505 --> 29:37.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just walked up to people in the
morning and
handed them either a $5 or a $5
bill, which

29:37.576 --> 29:40.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we asked them to spend by the
end of the day.
And there was a catch. We told
some people

29:40.979 --> 29:43.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they had to spend the money on
themselves.
We told some people they had to
spend the

29:43.915 --> 29:45.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
money on somebody else.

29:45.851 --> 29:49.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we found was that
people who'd been
randomly assigned to spend this
money on somebody

29:49.321 --> 29:52.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
else felt better by the end of
the day than
people who'd been assigned to
spend that same

29:52.658 --> 29:54.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
small amount of money on
themselves.

29:54.493 --> 30:00.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A small experiment,
small money,
small number of subjects. And
Canadians are

30:00.198 --> 30:01.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
unusually nice, eh?

30:01.933 --> 30:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: So, we conducted
parallel
experiments in Canada, Uganda,
South Africa,

30:07.639 --> 30:12.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
as well as collecting
correlational data from
around the world. And what we
saw was that

30:12.678 --> 30:16.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in poor and rich countries
alike, people felt
happier when they had the chance
to spend

30:16.548 --> 30:18.450 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
money on others rather than
themselves.

30:18.483 --> 30:22.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Best of all,
though, is the chance
to spend it on others you can
actually see.

30:22.754 --> 30:26.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL NORTON: So, a lot of the
charitable
giving that a lot of us do, we
write a check

30:26.058 --> 30:30.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it goes somewhere. And we
can show that
that does make you happier, but
think of the

30:30.362 --> 30:33.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
difference between the check
goes into the
ether and you don't know what
happened with

30:33.932 --> 30:38.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the money, compared to you
really tangibly
see the impact that your money
had on another

30:38.770 --> 30:40.038 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
person.

30:40.072 --> 30:41.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Or even just the
imaginary effect
on a stuffie.

30:41.707 --> 30:45.243 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Can you give one to
giraffe?

30:45.277 --> 30:51.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But are all kids
equally altruistic?
Is there a normal distribution,
a kind of

30:51.817 --> 30:57.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bell curve, some give a lot and
are really
happy, some are not happy at
all, most in

30:57.522 --> 30:59.391 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the middle?

30:59.424 --> 31:02.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: It's actually
surprisingly
consistent. So, most of the
toddlers are happier

31:02.661 --> 31:05.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when they're giving than when
they're getting
the treats for themselves.

31:05.764 --> 31:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So what's that red
spot on the
brain?

31:08.166 --> 31:10.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH, Georgetown
University: So,
the red mark in the brain is an
area of functional

31:10.936 --> 31:13.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
activation in the region called
the amygdala.

31:13.138 --> 31:17.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Georgetown
University psychology
Professor Abigail Marsh measures
the brain

31:17.843 --> 31:24.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
activity of what she terms
extraordinary altruists,
people who donated a kidney to a
total stranger.

31:24.716 --> 31:29.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH: The amygdala is
part of what's
called the mammalian brain. It's
involved

31:29.221 --> 31:35.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with emotions like fear and it's
involved
in social processes, like, to
some extent,

31:35.660 --> 31:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
love and caring. This is an
image from a brain
scan that we did looking at
differences in

31:41.867 --> 31:47.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
amygdala activation in people
who had donated
a kidney to a stranger relative
to people

31:47.105 --> 31:49.074 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
who have not.

31:49.107 --> 31:54.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Her research, she
says, was unequivocal:
The altruistic amygdalas were
about 8 percent

31:54.079 --> 31:55.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
larger than normal.

31:55.914 --> 31:59.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH: Altruistic kidney
donors showed
increased activation in the
amygdala when

31:59.718 --> 32:05.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they saw somebody in distress,
which is the
opposite of people at the other
end of the

32:05.323 --> 32:09.661 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
compassion spectrum,
psychopaths, who show
reduced activation in the
amygdala when they

32:09.694 --> 32:10.796 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
see somebody in distress.

32:10.829 --> 32:13.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And in one study of
psychopaths'
brains:

32:13.999 --> 32:18.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH: Their amygdalas
were shown
to be 17 to 18 percent smaller
than that of

32:18.703 --> 32:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
controls, so this also seems to
be related
to having lower levels of
concern or compassion

32:24.843 --> 32:26.611 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for other people.

32:26.645 --> 32:28.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, Dr. Seuss was
right. The
Grinch's heart is really three
sizes too small?

32:28.713 --> 32:32.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH: Yes, I do use
that analogy
sometimes. In fact, maybe it was
his amygdala

32:32.484 --> 32:34.219 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that was too small.

32:34.252 --> 32:37.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So when people find
that giving
is more gratifying than
receiving, what's

32:37.322 --> 32:39.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
going on?

32:39.124 --> 32:41.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABIGAIL MARSH: Everything I
think we have
learned from our research is
consistent with

32:41.193 --> 32:47.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the idea that it is a good thing
and beneficial
for a person to be giving and
generous to

32:47.833 --> 32:49.134 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
other people.

32:49.167 --> 32:53.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Do you want to give the
last treat
to you or to Monkey?

32:53.305 --> 33:00.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: One last
experiment: the effect
of giving on blood pressure.
Professor Dunn

33:00.512 --> 33:06.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gave adults over 65 with high
blood pressure
pill bottles filled with money.

33:06.151 --> 33:11.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: We asked them to
take home
these pill bottles and open them
on specified

33:11.323 --> 33:17.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
days over the course of three
weeks. Now,
inside each bottle was actually
$20. And if

33:17.162 --> 33:20.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you look at the label, there are
some instructions
about what you should be doing
with that money.

33:20.699 --> 33:26.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Please spend this
money on someone
else by 4:30 p.m. at the date
listed below.

33:26.805 --> 33:32.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: Other people got
pill bottles
that looked very similar, except
the instruction

33:32.043 --> 33:33.078 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is a little bit different.

33:33.111 --> 33:34.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Please spend this
money on yourself.

33:34.913 --> 33:39.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH DUNN: So, everybody
was pretty happy
getting pill bottles filled with
money. But

33:39.384 --> 33:44.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when we measured their blood
pressure, both
before and after the study, what
we found

33:44.222 --> 33:48.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was that people who got these
pill bottles
telling them to spend the money
on somebody

33:48.260 --> 33:52.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
else showed a significant
reduction in their
blood pressure from the
beginning to the end

33:52.898 --> 33:54.699 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the study.

33:54.733 --> 33:57.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In contrast, people who got this
pill bottle
who were told to spend the money
on themselves

33:57.802 --> 34:00.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just showed no change from the
beginning to
the end.

34:00.138 --> 34:04.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Now, Dunn insists
we issue this
warning. No matter how generous
the hypertense

34:04.976 --> 34:09.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
among you become after watching
this story,
please do not give up your blood
pressure

34:09.648 --> 34:11.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
medication just yet.

34:11.983 --> 34:17.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you want a quick ticket
to happiness,
it seems, whether your stash is
in gold or

34:17.155 --> 34:20.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
goldfish, give it away. You will
be happy
you did.

34:20.191 --> 34:24.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From Washington, D.C., and
Boston, this is
economics correspondent Paul
Solman, happily

34:24.796 --> 34:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sharing this news with you, the
"PBS NewsHour"
audience.

34:35.006 --> 34:45.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As the Supreme Court
considers
yet another major affirmative
action case,

34:45.617 --> 34:50.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
tonight's Race Matters
conversation focuses
on what happens before students
get to college

34:50.956 --> 34:55.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when they grow up in mostly
segregated inner-city
schools.

34:55.126 --> 35:01.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"PBS NewsHour" special
correspondent Charlayne
Hunter-Gault is reporting a
year-long series

35:01.132 --> 35:04.602 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on solutions to the questions
raised by race.

35:04.636 --> 35:09.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, she talks with Pedro
Noguera, a professor
at the University of California,
Los Angeles,

35:09.607 --> 35:12.143 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who has found what can work.

35:12.177 --> 35:17.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Despite
an historic
Supreme Court ruling some 61
years ago outlawing

35:17.515 --> 35:23.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
segregated schools, today, huge
numbers of
students remain in separate and
unequal schools,

35:23.254 --> 35:25.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
most in inner cities.

35:25.056 --> 35:29.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it doesn't have to be that
way, says Pedro
Noguera, director of the Center
for Study

35:29.260 --> 35:34.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of School Transformation at
UCLA. I met him
in New York, where he was about
to speak with

35:34.399 --> 35:35.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a group of educators.

35:35.533 --> 35:38.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Professor Noguera, thank you so
much for joining
us.

35:39.004 --> 35:44.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sixty-one years after separate
and unequal
was ruled illegal, you say it's
still happening.

35:44.409 --> 35:46.177 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Why?

35:46.211 --> 35:47.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA, University of
California, Los
Angeles: Well, it's happening
because the

35:47.912 --> 35:52.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
courts have basically made it
very difficult
to continue to pursue
integration.

35:52.283 --> 35:56.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's after we made quite a
bit of progress
in this country, especially in
the South,

35:56.388 --> 35:59.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but now we know that schools in
the North
and the West are more segregated
now than

36:00.025 --> 36:05.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they were 30 years ago. So, we
now find ourselves
in a situation where not only
are schools

36:05.096 --> 36:10.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
increasingly racially separate,
but we're
also concentrating the poorest
children in

36:10.602 --> 36:12.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
schools that have the fewest
resources.

36:12.303 --> 36:14.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Why?

36:14.105 --> 36:18.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: I would say it's
a combination
of lack of investment in schools
that serve

36:18.243 --> 36:22.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
poor children and the fact that
we have no
longer the political will.

36:22.781 --> 36:29.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But you
have argued
that separate schools play a
role in perpetuating

36:29.954 --> 36:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
inequality, not just in the
schools, but in
general.

36:32.791 --> 36:34.692 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PEDRO NOGUERA: They do.

36:34.726 --> 36:40.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They do, because separate has
still been unequal
in education. The racially
separate schools,

36:40.899 --> 36:45.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even when the schools do a good
job, the learning
opportunities you have a child
will influence

36:45.303 --> 36:49.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the kind of college you go into,
the kind
of profession you have access
to, the kind

36:49.674 --> 36:51.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of income you earn.

36:51.643 --> 36:56.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so if we really are
interested in creating
a society that's more equal and
less characterized

36:56.214 --> 37:01.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by racial divisions, then we
need to put more
investment in education and
leveling the playing

37:01.086 --> 37:02.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
field and integrating our
schools.

37:02.954 --> 37:06.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: There
have been schools
that have started that are
supposed to be

37:06.691 --> 37:11.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
making up for these disparities,
like the
charter schools and magnet
schools.

37:11.229 --> 37:15.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What impact are those kinds of
schools having,
though, on public education?

37:15.500 --> 37:19.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Well, in fact,
many of the
charter schools are even more
segregated than

37:19.437 --> 37:21.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the public schools.

37:21.306 --> 37:24.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Middle-class families,
particularly middle-class
African-American families, want
integrated

37:24.542 --> 37:26.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
schools for their kids.

37:26.377 --> 37:30.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Not long
ago, Professor
Raj Chetty told me about an
experiment that

37:30.748 --> 37:36.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
took young people out of
segregated communities
into more integrated
communities. But even

37:36.121 --> 37:41.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he said that, while those were
successful,
you needed to fix those within
the community.

37:41.226 --> 37:45.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, you have some solutions and
some examples
where that works.

37:45.663 --> 37:47.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Yes, and --
because we do have
examples.

37:47.765 --> 37:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tulsa, Oklahoma, for example,
here, you have
a city, a very red state, the
best high school

37:54.339 --> 37:59.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in the city, Booker T.
Washington, is 50 percent
black, and it is a school that
the entire

37:59.043 --> 38:02.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
city looks up to. That should be
a model for
the country.

38:02.280 --> 38:05.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But why
is it a school
that everybody looks up to?

38:05.483 --> 38:07.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Because of the
quality of education
provided.

38:07.619 --> 38:11.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: You just
said that
there wasn't the will in these
communities.

38:11.456 --> 38:13.324 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So what happens in that case?

38:13.358 --> 38:16.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Well, Tulsa --
it's interesting,
because Tulsa has a very ugly
history. In

38:16.227 --> 38:20.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1924, there was the race riots
there, where
the black community was burned
to the ground,

38:20.064 --> 38:21.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Greenwood.

38:21.900 --> 38:25.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there has been an effort,
though, in Tulsa
to invest in early childhood
education. Every

38:25.737 --> 38:30.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
child gets quality early
childhood education.
Every school is a community
school.

38:30.842 --> 38:32.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: How did
it get to
that point?

38:32.410 --> 38:34.212 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Good question.

38:34.245 --> 38:38.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Hope Franklin, a great
historian, was
a leader in the effort in
promoting the idea

38:38.583 --> 38:42.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of reparations for black folks
in Tulsa. After
he died, his students...

38:42.654 --> 38:44.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: He was a
pre-Ta-Nehisi
Coates?

38:44.355 --> 38:44.989 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:45.023 --> 38:46.724 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: That's right.

38:46.758 --> 38:52.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And his students, white students
from Duke
University, took up the effort
to rebuild

38:52.697 --> 38:57.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Greenwood after he died. There
is a big monument
in Tulsa to John Hope Franklin
built by his

38:57.535 --> 39:01.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
former students, most of whom
are affluent
whites in Tulsa.

39:01.773 --> 39:06.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is an important part of
the history
too. It's, we make our greatest
advances when

39:06.411 --> 39:11.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's not just African-Americans
that are pushing
the issue, when whites, when
Latinos, when

39:11.649 --> 39:17.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Asians, when the mosaic of
America recognizes
that we can be a better nation
if we are working

39:17.722 --> 39:19.624 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
together, if we are serving each
other's interests.

39:19.657 --> 39:23.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, there are others
like it in
other parts of the country that
are showing

39:23.228 --> 39:29.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us that you don't have to wait
until we solve
the problem of poverty or
inequality. You

39:29.434 --> 39:32.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can do a lot in education now
that would help
to move our society forward.

39:32.770 --> 39:37.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But one
of the things
you have talked about is how
there are needs

39:37.342 --> 39:42.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
beyond just the basic education,
particularly
for urban students, and I guess
you mean predominantly

39:42.747 --> 39:44.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
African-American or children of
color.

39:44.515 --> 39:46.351 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PEDRO NOGUERA: Well, absolutely.

39:46.384 --> 39:48.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are many children in this
country -- because
we have the highest child
poverty rates of

39:48.987 --> 39:53.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all advanced nations; 22 percent
of kids in
this country come from families
at or below

39:53.791 --> 39:57.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the poverty level. So, we have a
lot of kids
coming to school who are hungry,
who don't

39:57.228 --> 40:01.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have adequate housing, whose
have basic needs
not being met.

40:01.099 --> 40:04.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
